# Optimal Prompt for Claude AI: Deep Project Finalization

You are a senior full-stack developer and QA reviewer. Your task is to complete the Speeda-app project to a secure, robust, and production-ready state, following best practices and the QA review below. Address all unfinished work, refactor non-recommended code, and ensure all business logic and security-sensitive features are correctly implemented in the backend. Be especially thorough in the following areas:

## Project Completion Checklist (Deep Review)

### 1. Remove or Refactor Mock/Static Data
- Eliminate all fallback to mock/static data in production code (e.g., campaigns, post edit).
- Ensure all data flows use real API endpoints and database integration.

### 2. Refresh Token & Session Security
- Audit all refresh token logic (front and back):
  - Ensure refresh tokens are never exposed to client-side JavaScript or stored in localStorage. Use httpOnly, secure cookies for refresh tokens.
  - Move all refresh token issuance, storage, and renewal logic to the backend. The frontend should only receive new access tokens via secure endpoints.
  - Remove any refresh token handling in the frontend (e.g., localStorage, direct renewal calls).
- Implement proper token rotation and revocation (e.g., invalidate old refresh tokens on use or logout).
- Ensure all JWT secrets and expiry settings are managed via environment variables and never hardcoded.

### 3. Core Business Logic Placement
- Review all business logic and security-sensitive features:
  - Move any business logic, validation, or security checks from the frontend to the backend (e.g., token validation, user role checks, payment processing, analytics aggregation).
  - The frontend should only handle UI and call backend APIs for all sensitive operations.
- Refactor any direct database or sensitive API access out of the frontend.

### 4. Robust Error Handling & User Feedback
- Review all API calls and hooks (e.g., useTokens, useAnalytics, usePosts) for proper loading and error state management.
- Provide clear user feedback for all error cases.

### 5. Consistent Naming & Code Structure
- Standardize naming conventions for variables, functions, and files (especially case normalization and platform keys).
- Refactor deeply nested callbacks or excessive inline logic into reusable hooks or utility functions.

### 6. Form Validation & Navigation
- Ensure all forms (auth, setup, profile, etc.) validate input on both client and server.
- Review navigation logic for edge cases (router.replace vs router.push).

### 7. Documentation
- Document all assumptions about case handling, data normalization, and error boundaries.
- Update developer documentation for onboarding and maintenance.

### 8. Environment & Deployment
- Create .env.development and .env.production files with all required configuration parameters (database, API keys, secrets, etc.).
- Build a production-ready Dockerfile that includes:
  - The Next.js app
  - Database service (e.g., PostgreSQL)
  - All required environment variables and secrets
  - Health checks and secure production settings
- Provide docker-compose.yml for local and production orchestration (app + database).

### 9. Final QA & Testing
- Perform end-to-end testing of all user workflows.
- Ensure no static or mock data remains in production.
- Review and resolve all issues from the QA review.
- Test refresh token rotation, session expiry, and logout flows for security.
- Test that all business logic and sensitive operations are only accessible via backend APIs.

